[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Model monitoring.** Models degrade. Population composition shifts around open enrollment. Benefit designs change annually. New competitors enter markets. If you don't monitor prediction quality against ground truth, you'll deploy a model that slowly becomes useless and not notice until retention numbers drop months later. This step runs monthly on a schedule offset from scoring (you need time for outcomes to materialize before you can evaluate predictions). It is especially important around open enrollment periods when the population composition shifts most dramatically.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION monitor_model_performance(scoring_date_to_evaluate):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Look back at predictions from 90 days ago and compare against actual outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Why 90 days? That's the prediction horizon: we predicted "will this member
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // churn within 90 days?" Now we know whether they actually did.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     evaluation_date = scoring_date_to_evaluate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     prediction_date = evaluation_date - 90 days
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load predictions we made 90 days ago.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     historical_predictions = load from S3:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         s3://churn-scoring-results/scores/date={prediction_date}/members.parquet
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load actual outcomes: who actually disenrolled between then and now?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     actual_outcomes = query eligibility system:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         for each member in historical_predictions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             label = 1 if member disenrolled between prediction_date and evaluation_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             label = 0 otherwise
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Join predictions to actuals on member_id.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     evaluation_set = join historical_predictions with actual_outcomes on member_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute rolling AUC-PR (precision-recall area under curve).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // AUC-PR is the right metric for imbalanced problems: it tells you how well
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // the model distinguishes churners from non-churners in the minority class.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     auc_pr = compute AUC-PR(evaluation_set.churn_probability, evaluation_set.actual_label)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute Expected Calibration Error (ECE).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // ECE measures how well calibrated the probabilities are: when the model says
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "60% chance of churn," do roughly 60% of those members actually churn?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Bin predictions into 10 equal-width bins, compare predicted vs. actual rate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ece = compute ECE(evaluation_set.churn_probability, evaluation_set.actual_label, bins=10)
